=========================================
std::unique_ptr (C++11)
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is std::unique_ptr?

std::unique_ptr is a C++11 smart pointer that provides
exclusive ownership of a dynamically allocated object and
automatically deletes it when it goes out of scope (RAII).

-----------------------------------------

2. Why unique_ptr?

Problems with raw pointers

• Memory leaks
• Dangling pointers
• Double deletion
• Exception safety

unique_ptr automatically manages memory using RAII.

-----------------------------------------

3. Key Properties

• Exclusive ownership
• Cannot be copied
• Can be moved
• Automatic cleanup (RAII)
• Lightweight (no reference counting)

-----------------------------------------

4. Declaration

#include <memory>

unique_ptr<int> p(new int(10));

Preferred (C++14)

auto p = make_unique<int>(10);

-----------------------------------------

5. Copy vs Move

Copy ❌

unique_ptr<int> p2 = p1;    // ERROR

Move ✔

unique_ptr<int> p2 = std::move(p1);

After move

p1 == nullptr
p2 owns the resource

-----------------------------------------

6. Why copy is deleted?

unique_ptr provides exclusive ownership.

Allowing copy would create two owners,
leading to double deletion.

-----------------------------------------

7. Why move is allowed?

Move transfers ownership from one unique_ptr
to another while ensuring there is only one owner.

-----------------------------------------

8. Member Functions

get()

Returns raw pointer.
Ownership unchanged.

release()

Releases ownership.
Returns raw pointer.

⚠ Caller must delete manually.

reset()

Deletes current object and optionally manages a new one.

reset();

Deletes object and becomes nullptr.

swap()

Exchanges ownership.

operator*

Dereference.

operator->

Access members.

operator bool

Checks whether pointer is valid.

-----------------------------------------

9. get() vs release()

get()

✔ Returns raw pointer
✔ Ownership retained

release()

✔ Returns raw pointer
✔ Ownership released
✔ Manual delete required

-----------------------------------------

10. make_unique()

Introduced in C++14.

Preferred over new because

• Cleaner
• Exception safe
• Avoids explicit new

-----------------------------------------

11. Custom Deleter

Used when delete is not the correct cleanup.

Examples

FILE*      → fclose()
Socket     → close()
HANDLE     → CloseHandle()

Example

auto deleter = [](FILE* fp)
{
    fclose(fp);
};

unique_ptr<FILE, decltype(deleter)>
file(fopen("a.txt","r"), deleter);

Why decltype?

Every lambda has a unique compiler-generated type.

-----------------------------------------

12. Passing unique_ptr to Functions

Read Only

void foo(const unique_ptr<T>& p);

Modify Object

void foo(unique_ptr<T>& p);

Take Ownership

void foo(unique_ptr<T> p);

foo(std::move(ptr));

If function only needs the object,
prefer passing T* or T& instead of unique_ptr.

-----------------------------------------

13. unique_ptr vs shared_ptr

unique_ptr

• Single owner
• No reference counting
• Faster
• Default choice

shared_ptr

• Multiple owners
• Reference counting
• More overhead

-----------------------------------------

14. When to Use

✔ Default smart pointer
✔ Exclusive ownership
✔ RAII
✔ Factory functions
✔ Resource management

-----------------------------------------

15. Interview Questions

Q. Why is unique_ptr non-copyable?

Exclusive ownership prevents multiple owners and double deletion.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Why is move allowed?

Ownership can be transferred safely while maintaining a single owner.

-----------------------------------------

Q. get() vs release()?

get() returns the raw pointer without releasing ownership.

release() returns the raw pointer and releases ownership.
The caller must delete it manually.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Why make_unique?

Cleaner, exception-safe, and preferred over explicit new.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Why custom deleter?

Some resources require cleanup other than delete,
such as FILE*, sockets, or OS handles.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Why is the constructor explicit?

To prevent accidental implicit ownership transfer
from raw pointers.

-----------------------------------------

30-Second Interview Answer

std::unique_ptr is a C++11 smart pointer that provides exclusive ownership of a 
dynamically allocated object. It automatically releases memory using RAII, cannot be copied, 
but can be moved to transfer ownership. It is lightweight because it has no reference counting and 
is the default smart pointer whenever shared ownership is not required.

